### [Fairy shrimps](../species/sp_anostraca.qmd)

South African fairy shrimps (Anostraca) species represent habitat specialists that occupy temporary freshwater habitats.In 2023, the first comprehensive assessment of South African Anostraca was initiated through the [NRF FBIP REFRESH Project](https://saiab.ac.za/platforms/fresh-water-field-unit/refresh-project/). This contributes 58% of the [global Anostraca IUCN assessments](https://www.iucnredlist.org/search?permalink=41b6a04f-4ca0-47a8-8d57-65277bde5581), making a sizeable contribution to the understanding of the current state of these temporary freshwater habitat indicator species. Of the [36 species assessed](https://www.iucnredlist.org/search?permalink=738fb169-a7d9-4fa5-8874-2f43b795e55e), 25% (9 species) were found to be threatened with extinction (@fig-1 and @tbl-1). The main driver of threat was habitat loss and degradation due to urban expansion and agricultural activities. These species' habitats are varied and include endorheic (internally drained) wetlands, remnant riverine pools, rock pools, roadside ditches, and even animal wallows. These habitats are not permanent features in the landscape and hence are impacted by activities when they are not inundated. An increase in awareness is needed to protect these highly diverse and dynamic habitats. In recent years, there has been some interest in sampling and identifying these species using both morphology and genetic tools. This has led to the discovery of new species [@Rogers2021], as well as range extensions.

### [Freshwater fishes](../species/sp_fwf.qmd)

South Africaâs freshwater fishes are the second most threatened comprehensively assessed taxonomic group [(see ecosystem threat status)](../integrated-findings/intf_ecosystems.qmd), with 36% (42 taxa) assessed as threatened, and when only considering endemics, 66% (38) are threatened (@fig-1 and @tbl-1). Freshwater fish have not been reassessed since 2018, but field observations and the status of South African rivers and wetlands indicate that pressures have not ceased and continue to mount [(see freshwater ecosystem condition)](../integrated-findings/intf_pressures-condition.qmd)). A breakthrough for this group since the last assessment in 2018 has been an immense investment in the expansion of the taxonomic understanding of many freshwater fishes, through resolving species complexes and describing new species (see [Box 1](#box-1)). These taxonomic advances are critical to enable Red List assessment updates. Along with taxonomic updates of many species, a large number of field surveys have improved our understanding of active threats and the condition of the habitats of many fishes.

::: {#box-1 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 1. REFRESH: filling knowledge gaps on freshwater species of South Africa" collapse="true"}
<img src="imgs/refresh_logo.png" alt="box_1_img_3" style="width:30%; float:left; margin-right:15px;"/> The NRF Foundational Biodiversity Information Programme (FBIP) [REFRESH project](https://saiab.ac.za/platforms/fresh-water-field-unit/refresh-project/) aimed to address key knowledge gaps for seven freshwater taxonomic groups: freshwater fishes, molluscs, large branchiopods (fairy shrimps), freshwater crabs, freshwater fish parasites, amphibians, and odonates (dragonflies and damselflies). Each group defined specific objectives to improve data on species delimitation, distribution, habitat condition, and key pressures. Capacity building, student training, and raising awareness of freshwater biodiversity were also core outcomes of the project. More than 40 co-investigators and collaborators contributed to the project, which ran from 2021 to 2025, implemented by SANBI and SAIAB. Data generated through the project have contributed to Red List assessments, expanded DNA barcoding collections, and will be used to establish and update baseline datasets for detecting change, assessing river and wetland condition, and informing strategic freshwater management and decision-making.
:::

Major pressures that have persisted for freshwater fishes and their habitat are competition with invasive alien fish and degradation of their freshwater habitat through water abstraction, pollution, and inappropriate sedimentation. Many emerging pressures have been identified through recent surveys, but their impacts on freshwater fishes will be interpreted and accounted for within the next update of the Red List of South African freshwater fishes. Of particular concern is illegal mining activity in the north-eastern regions of the country within river systems hosting highly threatened and restricted fishes (e.g. [*Enteromius treurensis*](https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/2572/100159826)) see [Box 2](#box-2).

The current list of freshwater fishes excludes migratory fishes such as the eel species present in South African freshwater and marine realms, thus representing a knowledge gap. Further work is required to enable comprehensive reporting on the state of migratory fish species.

:::: {#box-2 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 2. New active pressures in river systems that are impacting highly threatened species" collapse="true"}
Unregulated or illigal gold mining (commonly referred to as zama-zama activities in South Africa) presents an escalating threat to the Blyde, Sabi and lower Crocodile River tributaries in the Mpumalanga Province. Expansion of these activities is currently occurring with limited law enforcement or coordinated institutional response. Impacts include physical disturbance of riverbeds and banks, and the use of mercury and cyanide for gold extraction, with consequent cumulative risks to aquatic biota.

The Blyde River population of [*Enteromius treurensis*](https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/2572/100159826) (CR) is of particular concern. Habitat degradation in this system has intensified to the extent that **extinction of this taxon in the near future is plausible** if current pressures persist. The scale and nature of impacts indicate that an effective response will require coordinated, cross-sectoral intervention across relevant government departments.

