### [Birds](../species/sp_birds.qmd)

There are 166 birds associated with freshwater ecosystems (waterbirds), and of these, 133 have been assessed using the IUCN Regional Red List. Of these waterbirds, 14% (19 species) of the species are threatened with extinction and 28% (37 species) are taxa of conservation concern (TOCC) (threatened species, DD, Rare and NT) (@fig-1 and @tbl-1). Since the 2015 Red List assessment, there has been a sharp decline in the status of many waterbird species, with many species recently being uplisted from Least Concern to an IUCN threat category (see [Box 3](#box-3)). Of the thirty-nine bird species that have been uplisted to a higher threat category, nineteen are waterbirds (48% of uplisted birds are water birds).

::: {style="display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 10px; flex-wrap: wrap;"}
<figure style="margin: 0; text-align: left; flex: 1 1 100%;">

![](./imgs/fw_img_7.png){style="width:100%; height:auto; max-height:600px; object-fit:cover; margin-bottom: 5px;"}

<figcaption>The [greater flamingo](https://www.birdlife.org.za/red-list/greater-flamingo/) (*Phoenicopterus roseus*) is assesses as Near-Threatened in South Africa, an iconic wetland species, recent CWAC data indicate population declines within the assessment region. (Â©Â MartinÂ Taylor,Â AvesAfrica)</figcaption>

</figure>
:::

<br> An few examples is the [African darter](https://www.birdlife.org.za/red-list/african-darter/) (*Anhinga rufa*) which has experienced a significant decline in its habitat availability through habitat loss (e.g. wetland drainage), impacts on breeding sites and environmental pollution (e.g. pesticide use and run-off, effluent). The [maccoa duck](https://www.birdlife.org.za/red-list/maccoa-duck/) (*Oxyura maccoa*), has been uplisted from Near Threatened to Vulnerable, due to the impacts of invasive alien species (e.g., water hyacinth (*Eichhornia crassipes*)) in its wetland habitats. The [half-collared kingfisher](https://www.birdlife.org.za/red-list/half-collared-kingfisher/) (VU) (*Alcedo semitorquata*) provides an example of a habitat specialist dependent on fast-flowing, clear, perennial streams and rivers that offer sheltered conditions and dense marginal vegetation. These types of habitats are increasingly threatened by pollution, siltation, and reduced flow due to over-abstraction of water and prolonged drought.

::: {style="display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 10px; flex-wrap: wrap;"}
<figure style="margin: 0; text-align: left; flex: 1 1 100%;">

![](./imgs/fw_img_8.png){style="width:100%; height:auto; max-height:600px; object-fit:cover; margin-bottom: 5px;"}

<figcaption>[Yellow-billed stork](https://www.birdlife.org.za/red-list/yellow-billed-stork/) (*Phoenicopterus roseus*), is globally Least Concern, but in South Africa it is assessed as Vulnerable due to loss of habitat in wetlands, on which it depends for foraging. (Â©Â MartinÂ Taylor,Â AvesAfrica)</figcaption>

</figure>
:::

<br> Besides habitat loss, many of these waterbirds are congregatory in nature, which makes them vulnerable to disease outbreaks. Waterbirds merit increased protection at key protected areas to prevent accelerated rates of decline. Urban freshwater habitats present unique opportunities for citizen-led habitat restoration and monitoring.

::: {#box-3 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 3. Waterbirds are declining in South Africa, based on the most recent Regional assessment for South African birds led by BirdLife South Africa" collapse="true"}
Waterbirds are integral to the healthy ecological function of wetland and temporary aquatic systems, where they contribute to nutrient cycling, regulate plant and insect populations, and act as sensitive indicators of ecosystem health. Their presence signals functioning temporary habitats such as pans, mudflats, and ephemeral wetlands that support a wide range of biodiversity. Because many waterbirds depend on shallow, short-lived waterbodies, any change in hydroperiod, water quality, or habitat structure quickly affects their survival, breeding and migration.

Recent monitoring through the [Coordinated Waterbird Count](https://cwac.birdmap.africa/) (CWAC) programme shows that many waterbird species are declining, likely driven by prolonged droughts, climate-driven shifts in rainfall and temperature, and the resulting destabilisation of temporary wetlands. Climate change is altering the timing, depth, and duration of seasonal waterbodies, causing species like flamingos to disappear when pans dry too quickly or become too deep, and affecting species tied to specific habitat types such as mudflats or riverine thickets.

Human pressures are amplifying these trends. Wetlands are drained for agriculture and development, polluted by runoff and waste, disturbed by recreation, and invaded by alien plants that choke natural systems. In general, dams and diversions reduce river flow, while farm dams in particular provide poor-quality substitutes with depleted food webs. These combined pressures threaten species entirely dependent on intact wetlands. Conservation frameworks such as the Ramsar Convention â supported by monitoring efforts like CWAC â are critical to protecting temporary wetland systems, sustaining waterbird populations, and maintaining the broader ecological functions they underpin.

Monitoring waterbirds is vital to see how they are navigating these types of change. You can get involved by joining citizen-science monitoring programmes like CWAC to track changes and inform conservation actions. Visit [cwac.birdmap.africa](cwac.birdmap.africa) or enquire at your local bird club to find out more.
:::

### [Reptiles](../species/sp_reptiles.qmd)

Of the 407 reptile species indigenous to South Africa, 15 species are dependent on freshwater habitats. Four of the 15 species (20%) are taxa of conservation concern (ToCC), three of these are assessed as Vulnerable, and one is assessed as Data Deficient (@fig-1 and @tbl-1). The major pressures on these ToCC are natural system modification and pollution, which are impacting all threatened species, followed by 66% of ToCC impacted by agricultural and mining activities, causing habitat degradation (@fig-3). Climate change and its associated effects on weather patterns and temperature have been identified as a current or potential future threat to some threatened reptile species. However, more monitoring is required to fully understand these impacts in South Africa. Increase in intensity of fires and a change in the timing of seasonal burns may affect these species during their hibernation period. While no freshwater-associated species have experienced a change in their IUCN Red List status, resulting in the RLI remaining stable, there has still been a continuation and exacerbation of pressures within these species' habitats.

See [the Conservation assessment of South African reptiles](https://www.sanbi.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/2023_Suricata10.pdf) for more details.

:::: {#box-4 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 4. Risks of alien freshwater crayfish introductions to South Africa" collapse="true"}
Alien freshwater crayfish have been widely introduced worldwide for aquaculture and the pet trade. Despite providing societal benefits, crayfish introductions are also known to cause adverse impacts in areas of introduction. A recent study evaluated the risk associated with 14 alien freshwater crayfish introductions in South Africa, most of which were classified as high risk due to their potential for major negative effects [@BothaInPress]. Eight crayfish species are listed on the NEM: BA A&IS Regulations and are presumed to be present in South Africa based on historical introduction [@Wilson2024]. However, uncertainty remains about the identity and occurrence of some species. *Cherax cainii* and *C. tenuimanus* were introduced for aquaculture, but it is uncertain if both species are present, and genetic verification is needed to confirm their presence. Similarly, *Cherax destructor* was also introduced for aquaculture, but its presence, in cultivation or in the wild, is unclear.

Evidence indicates that *Cherax quadricarinatus* and *Procambarus clarkii* have established populations across several river systems. Containment has been proposed as the primary management strategy. *Procambarus clarkii* is not listed under the A&IS Regulations; it was previously listed as a prohibited species but was removed from the regulations in 2021, creating legal uncertainty that may have facilitated its spread. Anecdotal evidence suggests that five other crayfish species (*Faxonius limosus*, *F. rusticus*, *Pontastacus leptodactylus*, *Pacifastacus leniusculus*) listed under the A&IS Regulations are also present in South Africa, likely due to the pet trade- a significant invasion pathway that is difficult to manage. Several other crayfish species that have a global invasion history (*Faxonius immunis*, *F. juvenilis*, *F. virilis*, *Procambarus acutus* and *P. virginalis*) are not yet present in South Africa, highlighting a substantial invasion debt. Management options should prioritise preventing further introductions.

::: {style="display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 10px; flex-wrap: wrap;"}
